text.tspan: This tutorial covers shape and node editing, freehand and bezier drawing,
path manipulation, booleans, offsets, simplification, and text tool.
Use Ctrl+arrows or middle mouse button drag to scroll the page down.
For basics of object creation, selection, and transformation, see the Basic
tutorial in Help > Tutorials.
General tips
Editing ellipses
From ellipses, you can create various segments and arcs:
If you stay inside the ellipse when dragging its handle, you're
creating an arc; otherwise, a segment. Pressing Ctrl will limit your
radius angle to 15 degree increments. Note that the arcs (two
rightmost shapes above) are unclosed shapes, i.e. the stroke only
goes along the ellipse but does not connect the ends of the arc.
Spiral is a quite versatile shape. Using the two handles, you can vary
the spiral's diameter and "unroll" it from inside. More interesting
modifications are available via the top panel controls.
Editing spirals
You can set the total number of turns (revolutions), the radius of the
innermost revolution, and the divergence value which controls
how much denser or sparser are the outer revolutions compared to
the inner ones (the value of 1 means equal distances between
revolutions everywhere).
The star tool has two modes, star and polygon. Switch between them
by checking or unchecking the Polygon checkbox in the top panel.
Polygons are just regular polygons with one handle controlling their
size. Stars are a much more interesting shape with two handles that
can be positioned arbitrarily, producing a great variety of
central-symmetric shapes.
Editing stars
::SHAPES
Inkscape has several versatile shape tools, each creating its own kind
of shapes. A shape is an object which has certain draggable handles
and numeric parameters, allowing you to twist and bend the shape
without losing its capabilities.
For example, with a star you can
alter the number of rays, their
length and angle, but a star remains a star.
A shape is thus more
limited
than a simple path, but often more
convenient and interesting.
You
can convert a shape to a path, but
not back.
The shape tools are Rectangle, Ellipse, Star, and Spiral. First we'll
look at how shape tools work in general, then we'll explore
each one
in detail.
A new shape is created by dragging on canvas with the
corresponding tool
Once the shape is created (and so long as it is
selected), it displays
its handles as white diamonds, so you can at
once edit what you
created by dragging them.
All four kinds of shapes display their
handles in all four
shape tools
as well as in the Node tool (F2). When you hover your mouse over a
handle, it displays a tip in the
statusbar explaining what it does by
simple drag as well as with different modifiers. Some handles can
do things also by clicking on them.
Also, each shape tool has some controls on the Tool Controls bar
(which runs horizontally at the top of the window). Usually it
provides a few numeric entry fields and a button to reset the values
to defaults. When object(s) of its native kind are selected, changing
the values in the tool's Controls bar affects the selected shapes.
Selecting an object can be
done by clicking on it right in a shape
tool; Esc deselects.
Also, any changes to the Tool Controls
settings are rememered and
used for the
next object
you create with that tool. For example,
when you
change the number of rays of a star, new stars will have
this
number of rays as well. Moreover, even simply selecting a
shape sends it parameters to the Controls bar and thus sets the
parameters of the new shapes of this type.
Rectangles
A rectangle is the simplest but likely the most common shape in
design and illustration. Inkscape attempts to make creating and
editing rectangles as easy and convenient as possible.
Switch to the Rectangle tool by F4 or by clicking its toolbar button.
Draw a rectangle alongside this one:
Then, without leaving the Rectangle tool, switch selection from one
rectangle to the other by clicking on them.
Rectangle drawing shortcuts:
With Ctrl, draw a square or a integer-ratio rectangle.
With Shift, draw around the starting point as center.
As you see, a selected rectangle (the just-drawn rectangle is always
selected) shows three handles in three
corners. In fact, these are
four handles, but two of them
(normally in the top right corner)
overlap if the rectangle is not
rounded. These two are the rounding
handles; the other two
(top left and bottom right) are resize
handles.
Let's look at the rounding handles first. Grab one of them and drag
down. All four corner of ther rectangle become rounded, and you
can now see the second rounding handle - it stays in the original
position in the corner. If you want simple rounded corners, that is
all you need to do. If you want corners which are rouded farther
along one side than along the other, you can move that other
handle leftwards.
Here, the first two rectangles have uniform rounded corners (the
second handle is not used), and the other two have non-uniform
rounded corners:
Still in the Rectangle tool, click on these rectangles to select and
observe the rounding handles.
Often, the radius and the shape of the rounded corners are to be
constant within the entire composition, even if the sizes of the
rectangles are different (think diagrams with rounded boxes of
various sizes). Inkscape makes this easy. Switch to the Selector
tool; in its Controls panel, there's a group of toggle buttons, the
second one from the left showing two concentric rounded corners.
This is how you control whether the rounded corners are scaled
when the rectangle is scaled or not.
For example, here the original red rectangle is duplicated and scaled
several times, up and down, to different proportions, with the "scale
rounded corners" button off:
draw here
Note how the size and shape of the rounded corners are the same
in all rectanfles, so
that the corners coincide exactly in the top right
corner where they all meet. All the dotted blue rectangles are
obtained from the source red rectangle by simple scaling in selector,
without
readjusting the rounding handles.
For a comparison, here is the same composition but now created
with
the "scale rounded corners" button on:
Now the rounded corners are as different as the rectangles they
belong to, and there isn't a slightest agreement in the top right
corner (zoom in to see). The same visible result you could also get by
converting the
original rectangle to a path (Ctrl+Shift+C) and
scaling it as path.
Here are the shortcuts for the rounding handles of a rectangle:
Drag with Ctrl to make the other radius the same.
Ctrl+click to make the other radius the same without dragging.
Shift+click to remove rounding.
You may have noticed that the Controls bar shows the horizontal (Rx)
and
vertical (Ry) rounding radii for the selected rectangle and lets you
set
them precisely using any length units. The "Not rounded" button
does
what is says - removes rounding from the selected rectangle(s).
An
important advantage of these controls is that they can affect many
rectangles at once.
Now let's look at the resize handles of a rectangle. You might wonder,
why do we need them at all, if we can just as well resize the rectangle
with Selector?
The problem with Selector is that its notion of horizontal and vertical
is always that of the document page. By contrast, a rectangle's resize
hadles scale it along that rectangle's sides, even if the rectangle is
rotated or skewed. For example, try to resize this rectangle first
with Selector and then within its resize handles in Rectangle tool:
Since the resize handles are two, you can resize the rectangle into
any direction or even to move it along its sides. Resize handles
always preserve the rounding radii.
Here are the
shortcuts for the resize handles:
Here is the same rectangle, with the gray dotted lines showing the
directions to which the resize handles stick when dragged with
Ctrl (try it):
Drag with Ctrl to snap to the sides or the diagonal of the rectangle.
In other words, Ctrl preserves either width, or height, or the
width/height proportion of the rectangle (again, in its own
coordinate system which may be rotated or skewed).

resizing with its resize handles, perspective
